    <statement><p>Calculate the following. Use an improper fraction in your answer.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{ \frac{1}{2} - \frac{5}{4} }{ \frac{5}{6} } =}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-{\frac{9}{10}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simplify a complex fraction, we find the common denominator of all fractions. In this case, it is <m>12</m>. We multiply the complex fraction<rsq/>s numerator and denominator by this common denominator, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{ \frac{1}{2} - \frac{5}{4} }{ \frac{5}{6} } 
      \amp = \frac{(\frac{1}{2}-\frac{5}{4})\cdot 12}{ \frac{5}{6} \cdot 12 } \\
      \amp = \frac{\frac{1}{2} \cdot 12 - \frac{5}{4} \cdot 12}{ \frac{5}{6} \cdot 12 } \\
      \amp = \frac{6 - 15}{10 } \\
      
      \amp = {-{\frac{9}{10}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Here is a simple way to do fraction multiplication:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \frac{1}{2} \cdot 12 = 12 \div 2 \cdot 1 = 6 }</m></p>
</solution>
